  • All input features are typed as either int64 or float64 which is appropriate for numerical and categorical encoding tasks

Step 8: Apply SMOTE for Class Balancing

In[]:
# Separate features and target
X = df.drop('Target', axis=1)
y = df['Target']

# Convert target variable to numerical format
y_encoded = y.map({'graduate': 0, 'dropout': 1, 'enrolled': 2})

# Split the data into train and test sets (80-20)
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y_encoded, test_size=0.2, random_state=42, stratify=y_encoded)

# Apply one-hot encoding to categorical variables (if any)
X_train_encoded = pd.get_dummies(X_train)
X_test_encoded = pd.get_dummies(X_test)

# Align columns of test set with training (in case of missing categories)
X_test_encoded = X_test_encoded.reindex(columns=X_train_encoded.columns, fill_value=0)

# Apply SMOTE to training data only
smote = SMOTE(random_state=42)
X_train_balanced, y_train_balanced = smote.fit_resample(X_train_encoded, y_train)

# Format and display class distribution after SMOTE
smote_counts = pd.Series(y_train_balanced).value_counts().sort_index()
smote_percent = pd.Series(y_train_balanced).value_counts(normalize=True).sort_index() * 100

smote_labels = {0: 'Graduate', 1: 'Dropout', 2: 'Enrolled'}
smote_df = pd.DataFrame({
    'Count': smote_counts,
    'Percentage': smote_percent.round(2)
})
smote_df.index = smote_df.index.map(smote_labels)

# Display the new class distribution after SMOTE
print("Class distribution after applying SMOTE:\n")
display(smote_df)

print("Feature scaling complete.")

    print(f"PCA reduced to {X_pca.shape[1]} features")
except Exception as e:
    raise RuntimeError("PCA failed: " + str(e))

# RFE with Logistic Regression (alternative)
try:
    base_model = LogisticRegression(max_iter=1000)
    rfe = RFE(base_model, n_features_to_select=20)
    X_rfe = rfe.fit_transform(X, y)

    print("RFE selected 20 best features.")
except Exception as e:

PCA (Principal Component Analysis):

Reduced to 1 feature: PCA transformed the original set of features into a single principal component. This suggests that most of the variance in the data is captured by one linear combination of the features. While this can be useful for dimensionality reduction, it may lose specific feature-level details which can be important in predictive modeling.

RFE (Recursive Feature Elimination):

Selected 20 features: RFE has identified the top 20 features that are most important for the model. By iteratively removing the least significant features, RFE ensures that the remaining features are the best predictors for the target variable.

Selected RFE Feature Names:

The chosen features span a mix of demographic, academic, and socio-economic factors, such as:

  • Demographic: Gender, Age at enrollment, International status, Scholarship holder

  • Academic performance: Curricular units from both the 1st and 2nd semesters, including credits, enrollment, approval, and grades

  • Socio-economic factors: Admission grade, Tuition fees up to date, Debtor status, Unemployment rate

  • Other factors: Displaced, Educational special needs

These features are likely to provide relevant and meaningful information for predicting the target variable. The presence of both academic and socio-economic features reflects the complexity of the data and the range of factors that may influence the outcome.

Observations:

  • The consistently lower precision, recall, and F1-score for the "enrolled" class across all three modelsLogistic Regression, Random Forest, and XGBoostindicates a challenge in accurately identifying this particular class. This may stem from class imbalance or overlapping feature distributions that make "enrolled" harder to distinguish from the "dropout" and "graduate" classes.

  • In such scenarios:

    • Precision suffers due to a high number of false positivesmany instances are incorrectly predicted as "enrolled".
    • Recall drops when the model fails to identify a significant portion of true "enrolled" cases.
    • F1-score, being the harmonic mean of precision and recall, captures this imbalance clearly and reflects the model's difficulty in handling this class.

  • This indicates that while the overall accuracy may look acceptable, the model is not equally effective across all classes, and struggles particularly with the "enrolled" category.

  • Random Forest shows the highest overall accuracy (76%) and offers the most balanced performance across all three classes. It performs particularly well for the "graduate" class and reasonably for "dropout", while still underperforming on "enrolled". Its strength lies in capturing non-linear feature interactions and handling noisy data, which helps improve general performance.

  • Logistic Regression, with an accuracy of 74%, performs surprisingly well given its linear assumptions. It achieves the highest recall (0.64) for the "enrolled" class, meaning it identifies more actual "enrolled" cases compared to the other models, but its low precision (0.42) indicates many false positives. The model likely struggles due to its inability to capture non-linear patterns, especially when features overlap between classes.

  • XGBoost, known for its ability to handle imbalanced datasets and learn complex relationships, achieves 75% accuracy but doesnt significantly outperform the other models. The performance drop, especially for the "enrolled" class, suggests that the current model may be overfitting to majority classes or has suboptimal hyperparameters. With further tuning (e.g., adjusting learning rate, class weights, or regularization), XGBoost could potentially outperform the others.

# Store confusion matrices and ROC data
confusion_data = []
roc_data = []

# Collect both confusion matrix and ROC curve data
def xgboost_rf_evaluate_model(model, X, y, model_name):
    y_pred = model.predict(X)
    cm = confusion_matrix(y, y_pred)
    confusion_data.append((cm, model.classes_, model_name))

    # Multiclass ROC preparation
    if len(np.unique(y)) > 2:
        y_bin = label_binarize(y, classes=model.classes_)
        y_score = model.predict_proba(X)
        fpr, tpr, roc_auc = {}, {}, {}
        for i in range(len(model.classes_)):
            fpr[i], tpr[i], _ = roc_curve(y_bin[:, i], y_score[:, i])
            roc_auc[i] = auc(fpr[i], tpr[i])
        roc_data.append((model_name, fpr, tpr, roc_auc, model.classes_))
    else:
        y_score = model.predict_proba(X)[:, 1]
        fpr, tpr, _ = roc_curve(y, y_score)
        roc_auc_val = auc(fpr, tpr)
        roc_data.append((model_name, {0: fpr}, {0: tpr}, {0: roc_auc_val}, model.classes_))

# Evaluate both models
xgboost_rf_evaluate_model(model_rf, X_test, y_test, "Random Forest")
xgboost_rf_evaluate_model(model_xgb, X_test, y_test, "XGBoost")

# === Plot Confusion Matrices Side by Side ===
fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(12, 5))
for idx, (cm, labels, name) in enumerate(confusion_data):
    disp = ConfusionMatrixDisplay(confusion_matrix=cm, display_labels=labels)
    disp.plot(ax=axes[idx], cmap=plt.cm.Blues, colorbar=False)
    axes[idx].set_title(f"Confusion Matrix: {name}")
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

# === Plot ROC Curves Side by Side ===
fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(14, 6))
for idx, (model_name, fpr, tpr, roc_auc, classes) in enumerate(roc_data):
    ax = axes[idx]
    if len(classes) > 2:
        for i in range(len(classes)):
            ax.plot(fpr[i], tpr[i], label=f"Class {classes[i]} (AUC={roc_auc[i]:.2f})")
    else:
        ax.plot(fpr[0], tpr[0], label=f"AUC = {roc_auc[0]:.2f}")
    ax.plot([0, 1], [0, 1], 'k--')
    ax.set_title(f"ROC Curve: {model_name}")
    ax.set_xlabel("False Positive Rate")
    ax.set_ylabel("True Positive Rate")
    ax.legend(loc="lower right")
    ax.grid(True)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

# Model Comparison Table

# 1. Re-encode entire target column fresh
label_encoder = LabelEncoder()
y_encoded = label_encoder.fit_transform(df['Target'])

# 2. Re-split dataset (for consistency)
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(
    X_model, y_encoded, test_size=0.2, stratify=y_encoded, random_state=42
)

# 3. Rebuild SMOTE version
sm = SMOTE(random_state=42)
X_res, y_res = sm.fit_resample(X_model, y_encoded)
X_train_sm, X_test_sm, y_train_sm, y_test_sm = train_test_split(
    X_res, y_res, test_size=0.2, stratify=y_res, random_state=42
)

# 4. Re-train all models from scratch on encoded labels
model_lr = LogisticRegression(max_iter=1000)
model_lr.fit(X_train, y_train)

model_rf = RandomForestClassifier(random_state=42)
model_rf.fit(X_train, y_train)

model_xgb = XGBClassifier(use_label_encoder=False, eval_metric='mlogloss')
model_xgb.fit(X_train, y_train)

model_rf_sm = RandomForestClassifier(random_state=42)
model_rf_sm.fit(X_train_sm, y_train_sm)

model_xgb_sm = XGBClassifier(use_label_encoder=False, eval_metric='mlogloss')
model_xgb_sm.fit(X_train_sm, y_train_sm)

# 5. Safe Model Comparison Block
results = []
model_variants = {
    "Logistic Regression": (model_lr, X_test, y_test),
    "Random Forest": (model_rf, X_test, y_test),
    "XGBoost": (model_xgb, X_test, y_test),
    "RF + SMOTE": (model_rf_sm, X_test_sm, y_test_sm),
    "XGB + SMOTE": (model_xgb_sm, X_test_sm, y_test_sm)
}

for name, (model, X_eval, y_eval) in model_variants.items():
    preds = model.predict(X_eval)

    # Guarantee integer format
    y_eval = np.array(y_eval, dtype=int)
    preds = np.array(preds, dtype=int)

    acc = accuracy_score(y_eval, preds)

Overall Model Comparison

The classification task revealed that the "Enrolled" class is the most difficult to predict due to class imbalance and possibly overlapping features. All base models struggled with this class, showing low recall and F1-scores.

  • Logistic Regression is the simplest and fastest model. It performed reasonably well for the "Dropout" and "Graduate" classes but had poor results for the "Enrolled" class. It's a good choice if model interpretability is more important than perfect accuracy.
  • Random Forest showed the best overall performance in terms of accuracy and balanced class metrics. It improved slightly over Logistic Regression for the "Enrolled" class and performed consistently well for the others. After hyperparameter tuning, its F1 score reached 0.76. Its a solid middle-ground modelaccurate, fairly interpretable, and reliable.
  • XGBoost was the strongest at predicting "Graduate" students but had slightly lower overall accuracy compared to Random Forest. It performed similarly to the other models for the "Enrolled" class. While it didnt outperform Random Forest here, it could do better with further tuning or on different datasets.
  • To address the class imbalance, SMOTE (Synthetic Minority Over-sampling Technique) was applied. This technique significantly improved the results for the "Enrolled" class by balancing the dataset.
  • With SMOTE, Random Forest became the best-performing model with an accuracy of 83% and a macro F1 score of 0.83. XGBoost also improved, reaching 82% accuracy and 0.81 F1, but still slightly trailed behind.

        y_score = model.predict_proba(X_test)[:, 1]
        fpr, tpr, _ = roc_curve(y_test, y_score)
        roc_auc_val = auc(fpr, tpr)
        roc_data.append((name, {0: fpr}, {0: tpr}, {0: roc_auc_val}, y_classes))

# === Plot Confusion Matrices ===
fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 5, figsize=(22, 4))
for idx, (cm, labels, name) in enumerate(confusion_data):
    disp = ConfusionMatrixDisplay(confusion_matrix=cm, display_labels=labels)
    disp.plot(ax=axes[idx], cmap=plt.cm.Blues, colorbar=False)
    axes[idx].set_title(f"{name}")
    axes[idx].grid(False)
plt.suptitle("Confusion Matrices", fontsize=16)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

# === Plot ROC Curves ===
fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 5, figsize=(24, 5))
for idx, (name, fpr, tpr, roc_auc, classes) in enumerate(roc_data):
    ax = axes[idx]
    if len(classes) > 2:
        for i in range(len(classes)):
            ax.plot(fpr[i], tpr[i], label=f"{classes[i]} (AUC={roc_auc[i]:.2f})")
    else:
        ax.plot(fpr[0], tpr[0], label=f"AUC = {roc_auc[0]:.2f}")
    ax.plot([0, 1], [0, 1], 'k--')
    ax.set_title(f"{name}")
    ax.set_xlabel("False Positive Rate")
    ax.set_ylabel("True Positive Rate")
    ax.legend(loc="lower right")
    ax.grid(True)
plt.suptitle("ROC Curves", fontsize=16)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

In[]:
# Fit PCA separately just to plot explained variance (retain all components)
pca_full = PCA().fit(X_res)

# Plot cumulative explained variance
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
plt.plot(np.cumsum(pca_full.explained_variance_ratio_), marker='o', linestyle='--', color='navy')
plt.xlabel('Number of Principal Components')
plt.ylabel('Cumulative Explained Variance')
plt.title('PCA - Cumulative Explained Variance')
plt.grid(True)
plt.axhline(y=0.95, color='r', linestyle='--', label='95% Threshold')
plt.legend()
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

Observations:

  • Rapid Initial Growth:

    • The curve exhibits a sharp ascent at the outset, signifying that the initial principal components account for the majority of the variance present in the dataset. For instance, approximately the first 20 to 30 components are responsible for explaining over 80% of the variance.

  • Quick Attainment of 95% Threshold:

    • The red dashed line at 0.95 (95%) represents a widely accepted benchmark for dimensionality reduction. According to the graph, around 50 principal components are adequate to capture 95% of the overall variance.

  • Diminishing Returns:

    • After reaching about 100 components, the curve levels off, indicating that any additional components provide minimal new information.
    • Incorporating more components beyond this threshold results in only slight improvements in explained variance while increasing the complexity of the model.

  • Implications for Use Cases:

    • Significant dimensionality reduction is achievable (for example, from over 200 features to approximately 50) while retaining most of the variance in the dataset. This approach aids in decreasing computational demands and may enhance model generalization without substantial loss of information.

# Step 1: Fit PCA on full SMOTE data (X_res)
pca_full = PCA().fit(X_res)

# Step 2: Calculate cumulative explained variance
explained_var = np.cumsum(pca_full.explained_variance_ratio_)

# Step 3: Get number of components that explain 95% variance
n_components_95 = np.argmax(explained_var >= 0.95) + 1
print(f"Number of components to retain 95% variance: {n_components_95}")

# Step 4: Apply PCA using only those components
pca = PCA(n_components=n_components_95, random_state=42)
X_pca = pca.fit_transform(X_res)

# Step 5: Train-test split using reduced data
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(
    X_pca, y_res, test_size=0.2, stratify=y_res, random_state=42
)

# Lists to store confusion matrix and ROC curve data for each model
confusion_data = []
roc_data = []

# Evaluate & collect CM + ROC
def evaluate_model(model, X, y, model_name):
    y_pred = model.predict(X)
    cm = confusion_matrix(y, y_pred)
    confusion_data.append((cm, model.classes_, model_name))

    if hasattr(model, "predict_proba"):
        if len(np.unique(y)) > 2:
            y_bin = label_binarize(y, classes=model.classes_)
            y_score = model.predict_proba(X)
            fpr, tpr, roc_auc = {}, {}, {}
            for i in range(len(model.classes_)):
                fpr[i], tpr[i], _ = roc_curve(y_bin[:, i], y_score[:, i])
                roc_auc[i] = auc(fpr[i], tpr[i])
            roc_data.append((model_name, fpr, tpr, roc_auc, model.classes_))
        else:
            y_score = model.predict_proba(X)[:, 1]
            fpr, tpr, _ = roc_curve(y, y_score)
            roc_auc_val = auc(fpr, tpr)
            roc_data.append((model_name, {0: fpr}, {0: tpr}, {0: roc_auc_val}, model.classes_))

# === Add all three models
evaluate_model(model_lr, X_test, y_test, "Logistic Regression")
evaluate_model(model_rf, X_test, y_test, "Random Forest")
evaluate_model(model_xgb, X_test, y_test, "XGBoost")

# Confusion Matrices
fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 5, figsize=(25, 5))
for idx, (cm, labels, name) in enumerate(confusion_data):
    disp = ConfusionMatrixDisplay(confusion_matrix=cm, display_labels=labels)
    disp.plot(ax=axes[idx], cmap=plt.cm.Blues, colorbar=False)
    axes[idx].set_title(f"Confusion Matrix: {name}")
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

# ROC Curves
fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 5, figsize=(28, 6))
for idx, (model_name, fpr, tpr, roc_auc, classes) in enumerate(roc_data):
    ax = axes[idx]
    if len(classes) > 2:
        for i in range(len(classes)):
            ax.plot(fpr[i], tpr[i], label=f"{classes[i]} (AUC={roc_auc[i]:.2f})")
    else:
        ax.plot(fpr[0], tpr[0], label=f"AUC = {roc_auc[0]:.2f}")
    ax.plot([0, 1], [0, 1], 'k--')
    ax.set_title(f"ROC Curve: {model_name}")
    ax.set_xlabel("False Positive Rate")
    ax.set_ylabel("True Positive Rate")
    ax.legend(loc="lower right")
    ax.grid(True)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

Key Takeaways

  • XGBoost (GridSearchCV) delivers the best overall performance:

    • Highest Accuracy: 0.84
    • Strongest F1-scores across all classes, especially enrolled at 0.82
    • Highest Macro Avg and Weighted Avg: 0.84

  • Random Forest (GridSearchCV) is also highly competitive and stable, ideal for faster tuning and interpretability.

  • The "Enrolled" class improved the most after One-Hot Encoding and SMOTE:

    • F1-score jumped from ~0.40 to ~0.80+ fixing the main model weakness before encoding.

  • PCA helped reduce dimensions without hurting performance, especially in tree-based models.

Final Recommendation

For best results:

  • Use One-Hot Encoding + SMOTE + GridSearchCV.
  • Choose XGBoost (GridSearchCV) for top-tier performance.
  • Choose Random Forest (GridSearchCV) for simplicity and efficiency.

Avoid skipping encoding raw categorical features can drastically reduce recall and F1-scores, especially for minority or complex classes like enrolled.
